<li id="cite_note-urlHandbook_to_Life_in_the_Medieval_World,_3-Volume_Set_-_Madeleine_Pelner_Cosman,_Linda_Gale_Jones_-_Google_Książki-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-urlHandbook_to_Life_in_the_Medieval_World,_3-Volume_Set_-_Madeleine_Pelner_Cosman,_Linda_Gale_Jones_-_Google_Książki_19-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFMadeleine_Pelner_CosmanLinda_Gale_Jones2009" class="citation book cs1">Madeleine Pelner Cosman; Linda Gale Jones (2009). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=-Jf5t1vFw1QC&amp;pg=PA407">"The Nusayriyya Alawis"</a>. <i>Handbook to Life in the Medieval World, 3-Volume Set</i>. Infobase Publishing. pp.&#160;406, 407. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-4381-0907-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-4381-0907-7"><bdi>978-1-4381-0907-7</bdi></a>. <q>The Alawis are a sect of extremist (<i>ghuluw</i>) Shiism, so called because of their doctrine of the deification of Ali ibn Abi Talib, the nephew of the prophet Muhammad. The movement was founded in the mid-ninth century by Muhammad ibn Nusayr al-Namiri, who also proclaimed that the 10th of the 12 Shiite imams, Ali ibn Hadi, possessed a divine nature. Alawi doctrine is secret, esoteric, and Gnostic in nature.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=The+Nusayriyya+Alawis&amp;rft.btitle=Handbook+to+Life+in+the+Medieval+World%2C+3-Volume+Set&amp;rft.pages=406%2C+407&amp;rft.pub=Infobase+Publishing&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-4381-0907-7&amp;rft.au=Madeleine+Pelner+Cosman&amp;rft.au=Linda+Gale+Jones&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-Jf5t1vFw1QC%26pg%3DPA407&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlawites" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://origins.osu.edu/article/alawites-and-fate-syria?language_content_entity=en">"Alawites and the Fate of Syria"</a>. <i>Origins</i>. The Ohio State University. 12 November 2013<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">4 May</span> 2023</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Origins&amp;rft.atitle=Alawites+and+the+Fate+of+Syria&amp;rft.date=2013-11-12&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Forigins.osu.edu%2Farticle%2Falawites-and-fate-syria%3Flanguage_content_entity%3Den&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlawites" class="Z3988"></span></span>
