<li id="cite_note-Feldman-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Feldman_21-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Feldman_21-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFFeldman2020" class="citation book cs1">Feldman, Noah (12 May 2020). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=ODu-DwAAQBAJ&amp;dq=alawites+are+arabs&amp;pg=PA79"><i>The Arab Winter: A Tragedy</i></a>. Princeton University Press. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-691-20144-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-691-20144-3"><bdi>978-0-691-20144-3</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Arab+Winter%3A+A+Tragedy&amp;rft.pub=Princeton+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2020-05-12&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-691-20144-3&amp;rft.aulast=Feldman&amp;rft.aufirst=Noah&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DODu-DwAAQBAJ%26dq%3Dalawites%2Bare%2Barabs%26pg%3DPA79&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlawites" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFNisan2002" class="citation book cs1">Nisan, Mordechai (2002). "6: Alawites: To Power and the Unknown". <i>Minorities in the Middle East</i> (2nd&#160;ed.). McFarland &amp; Company, Inc. p.&#160;116. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7864-1375-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7864-1375-1"><bdi>978-0-7864-1375-1</bdi></a>. <q><span class="cs1-kern-left"></span>'Alawite religious faith, that is the belief-system of the Nusairi sect, is rooted in a doctrine whose ideas reflect multiple theological and philo-sophical influences. ... Greek or gnostic conceptions of the divinity intersperse with human incarnation as a key element in its theology.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=6%3A+Alawites%3A+To+Power+and+the+Unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Minorities+in+the+Middle+East&amp;rft.pages=116&amp;rft.edition=2nd&amp;rft.pub=McFarland+%26+Company%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7864-1375-1&amp;rft.aulast=Nisan&amp;rft.aufirst=Mordechai&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlawites" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Sources:
<ul><li><cite id="CITEREFMadeleine_Pelner_CosmanLinda_Gale_Jones2009" class="citation book cs1">Madeleine Pelner Cosman; Linda Gale Jones (2009). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=-Jf5t1vFw1QC&amp;pg=PA407">"The Nusayriyya Alawis"</a>. <i>Handbook to Life in the Medieval World, 3-Volume Set</i>. Infobase Publishing. p.&#160;407. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-4381-0907-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-4381-0907-7"><bdi>978-1-4381-0907-7</bdi></a>. <q>Alawi doctrine is secret, esoteric, and Gnostic in nature. They believe that Ali ibn Abi Talib is the supreme eternal God...</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=The+Nusayriyya+Alawis&amp;rft.btitle=Handbook+to+Life+in+the+Medieval+World%2C+3-Volume+Set&amp;rft.pages=407&amp;rft.pub=Infobase+Publishing&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-4381-0907-7&amp;rft.au=Madeleine+Pelner+Cosman&amp;rft.au=Linda+Gale+Jones&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-Jf5t1vFw1QC%26pg%3DPA407&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlawites" class="Z3988"></span></li>
<li><cite id="CITEREFPragerPragerSpenger2016" class="citation book cs1">Prager, Laila; Prager, Michael; Spenger, Guido, eds. (2016). <i>Parts and Wholes</i>. LIT Verlag. p.&#160;146. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-3-643-90789-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-3-643-90789-9"><bdi>978-3-643-90789-9</bdi></a>. <q>A major difference between the Shia and the Alawi, however, is that the latter worship Ali as a manifestation of the divine essence and believe in the reincarnation and transmigration of souls.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Parts+and+Wholes&amp;rft.pages=146&amp;rft.pub=LIT+Verlag&amp;rft.date=2016&amp;rft.isbn=978-3-643-90789-9&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlawites" class="Z3988"></span></li></ul>
